The paper deals with a problem in computational geometry (chasing convex bodies) and proposes a new algorithm for it, which suggests cs.CG (Computational Geometry) as the most likely sub-category. The problem involves minimizing movement between consecutive output points, which involves optimization and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions competitive ratio and interplay between geometry and competitive ratio, which suggests cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) as a possible sub-category. The paper mentions that the algorithm works for any norm, which suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a new strategy for the problem, which involves designing and analyzing algorithms, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category as well.
